        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/a9183b8f0c72400a/text/000001255": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/a9183b8f0c72400a/text/000001255",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-a9183b8f0c72400a-f7c9a8 twpub-a9183b8f0c72400a-05dbf3 twpub-a9183b8f0c72400a-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"chapter\"><p>XXXVIII. &quot;Rhetoric&quot; (38): Rather &quot;the gift of speech&quot;; or perhaps the &quot;decree&quot; of the reasoning faculty.</p></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/a9183b8f0c72400a/text/000001256": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/a9183b8f0c72400a/text/000001256",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-a9183b8f0c72400a-f7c9a8 twpub-a9183b8f0c72400a-05dbf3 twpub-a9183b8f0c72400a-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"chapter\">\n</div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/a9183b8f0c72400a/text/000001257": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/a9183b8f0c72400a/text/000001257",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-a9183b8f0c72400a-f7c9a8 twpub-a9183b8f0c72400a-05dbf3 twpub-a9183b8f0c72400a-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"chapter\"><p>BOOK XI V. &quot;Cithaeron&quot; (6): Oedipus utters this cry after discovering that he has fulfilled his awful doom, he was exposed on Cithaeron as an infant to die, and the cry implies that he wishes he had died there. Sophocles, Oedipus Tyrannus, 1391.</p></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/a9183b8f0c72400a/text/000001258": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/a9183b8f0c72400a/text/000001258",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-a9183b8f0c72400a-f7c9a8 twpub-a9183b8f0c72400a-05dbf3 twpub-a9183b8f0c72400a-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"chapter\">\n</div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/a9183b8f0c72400a/text/000001259": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/a9183b8f0c72400a/text/000001259",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-a9183b8f0c72400a-f7c9a8 twpub-a9183b8f0c72400a-05dbf3 twpub-a9183b8f0c72400a-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"chapter\"><p>V. &quot;New Comedy...,&quot; etc. C. has here strayed from the Greek rather widely. Translate: &quot;and understand to what end the New Comedy was adopted, which by small degrees degenerated into a mere show of skill in mimicry.&quot; C. writes Comedia Vetus, Media, Nova. XII. &quot;Phocion&quot; (13): When about to be put to death he charged his son to bear no malice against the Athenians.</p></div></div>"
        },
        "$:/plugins/twpub/a9183b8f0c72400a/text/000001260": {
            "role": "text",
            "title": "$:/plugins/twpub/a9183b8f0c72400a/text/000001260",
            "type": "text/vnd.twpub",
            "text": "<div class=\"twpub-a9183b8f0c72400a-f7c9a8 twpub-a9183b8f0c72400a-05dbf3 twpub-a9183b8f0c72400a-6b4cd0\"><div class=\"chapter\">\n</div></div>"
        },
